boyfriend: &#34;have you ever had italian beef?&#34;

me: &#34;no.. i don&#39;t think so...&#34;

so off we go for some delicious juicy greasy italian beef. and it was fantasmic! a nice large italian beef with spicy peppers on time. i&#39;m in heaven and i&#39;m drooling just thinking about it :] we split one (because we went to naf naf right before) but i totally could&#39;ve eaten the whole thing by myself.

100% amazing. dude a place like this needed to open. I am so happy with everything I&#39;ve gotten there so far. even my typical Midwestern meat and potato eating fiancÃ© who didn&#39;t want to go here- yep, I had to drag him! but now he&#39;s hooked too! because they have food he likes and he wouldn&#39;t admit it but he was eating off of my chicken super food plate too! 
try the Chicken dumplings. you&#39;ll die. but in a good way. ;) 

love this place. it&#39;s so yummy!!!!!!!!!

Meh...The restaurant is nice, but when compared to the surrounding breakfast restaurants competing for the &#34;breakfast enthusiasts&#34;, this place is in the middle of the pack. The service was excellent. The waitstaff were very attentive to me and especially my younger daughters. Their raspberry ice tea was a very memorable experience for my daughter (she had 3 of &#39;em!). In short, we did not have a bad dining experience.

Where this restaurant missed the mark were the attention to details that affect the customer experience. Before a container of pancake syrup with a meal, someone needs to ensure that the handle does not have syrup residue on it, leaving it for the customer (me) to discover for themselves. My denver omelette  was overcooked. Eggs are pretty difficult to mess up, but there should not be significant &#34;browning&#34; on an omelet. The last detail that stood out was the absence of kiddie cups with no-spill lids. My girls were provided standard 12oz insulated coffee cups for their apple juice and iced tea (too for a &#34;kid&#39;s size&#34; in my opinion&#34;). This was the first sit-down breakfast restaurant I&#39;ve eaten at which did not provide kiddie cups. Not a big deal for the childless, but significant for families with toddler and kids who are prone to accidentally knocking things over while dining.

...and thus my response &#34;meh&#34;

FALSE ADVERTISING - CLOSED!

Before going for lunch on Friday 10/18/2013, we checked their &#34;website&#34; (which is their Facebook page) for specials (see screen shot); but in fact when we arrived the place was CLOSED with a sign on the door saying they were closed Thursday &amp; Friday 10/17 &amp; 10/18 for &#34;repairs.&#34;

The sign also stated to mention Tap-in at the other Hotel Arista restaurants including Sugar Toad for a 20% discount; so we went to Sugar Toad. Before getting seated, I asked the hostess-barmaid if the discount was valid, and when she said it was not, I asked to speak to the manager -- And she replied &#34;I&#39;m the supervisor.&#34;  

When we returned home, we checked their website; and again there was NOTHING on them being closed.

It&#39;s FALSE ADVERTISING to KNOWINGLY LURE patrons to come over when the place is closed.
